    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube measures airspeed by sensing the difference between the total pressure (ram air) and the static pressure of the surrounding air. The difference between these two pressures is then converted into an airspeed reading on the aircraft's instruments. If the pitot tube gets blocked, it stops capturing the dynamic pressure, which will cause the airspeed indicator to give an inaccurate or completely incorrect reading. This makes accurate speed control and safe flight impossible, so keeping it clear is crucial for flight safety.",
      "source": "target",
