    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i read somewhere about how bugs or even ice can cause the blockage. is there any way for a pilot to tell if it's a minor blockage or something more serious while they're actually flying?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pilots can often detect a blockage by observing how the airspeed indicator behaves, such as showing an unusually low or inconsistent speed, especially during changes in airspeeds. If the aircraft is flying at a known speed and the indicator disagrees significantly, it signals an issue. Furthermore, a pilot should monitor the stall warning horn or flap indicator if those systems rely on pitot pressure, as a blockage can affect them too.",
